Load and Clean Data

#Data contains 803 complete responses that passed all screening and attention checks
Data_SG <- read.csv("./FullRawData/MITei Mobility Culture Survey - Singapore_April 16, 2019_14.12.csv", stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
Data_SG <- Data_SG[3:nrow(Data_SG),]  #remove extra header rows


#RH_Use: Have you ever used these ridehailing services (as a passenger)?" 
# 1 = "No: I have never used a ridehailing service"
# 2 = "Yes: I have used a private (or exclusive) ridehailing service"
# 3 = "Yes: I have used a shared (or pooled) ridehailing service"

#Multiple selection of '1,2', '1,3', or '1,2,3' indicate inconsistency -- remove these responses
#Multiple selection of '2,3' is allowed
Data_SG <- subset(Data_SG, RH_Use!='1,2,3') #-1 response
Data_SG <- subset(Data_SG, RH_Use!='1,2')   #-1 response
Data_SG <- subset(Data_SG, RH_Use!='1,3')   #-0 responses

Summarize Sample Sociodemographics

Data_SG <- Data_SG %>% mutate(DOB = as.numeric(as.character(Age)),
                                    Age = 2019 - DOB,
                                    Age1 = ifelse(Age < 30, 1, 0),
                                    Age2 = ifelse(Age >= 30 & Age <= 44, 1, 0),
                                    Age3 = ifelse(Age >= 45 & Age <= 54, 1, 0),

#HHInc: What is your household monthly income (including employer CPF contributions, if applicable) in Singapore dollars?
#1=Below $1000=500, 2=$1000-2499=1750, 3=$2500-3999=3250, 4=$4000-4999=4500, (no 5), 
#6=$5000-5999=5500, 7=$6000-6999=6500, 8=$7000-7999=7500, 9=$8000-8999=9500, 
#10=$9000-9999=9500, 11=$10000-10999=10500, 12=$11000-12999=12000, 13=$13000-14999=14000, 
#(no 14), 15=$15000-17499=16250, (no 16), 17=$17500-19999=18750, 18=$20000 or more=21250, 
#19(unknown)
Data_SG$HHInc <- car::recode(Data_SG$HHInc, 
                             "1=500; 2=1750; 3=3250; 4=4500; 6=5500; 7=6500;
                             8=7500; 9=8500; 10=9500; 11=10500; 12=12000; 
                             13=14000; 15=16250; 17=18750; 18=21250")
Data_SG$HHInc <- Data_SG$HHInc / 1000

Data_SG$HHCars <- car::recode(Data_SG$HHCars, "1=0; 2=1; 3=2; 4=3")

#Employ:    Which option best describes your current employment status? 
# 1-Employed: full time, 2-Employed: part time, 
# 3-Self-employed: full time, 4-Self-employed: part time, 
# 5-Contributing family worker (assist in the operation of family business without receiving regular wages), 
# 6-Unemployed: looking for work, 7-Unemployed: unable to work or not looking for work, 8-Retired, 9-Student
Data_SG$FullTime <- car::recode(Data_SG$Employ, "c(1,3)=1; c(2,4,5,6,7,8,9)=0")
Data_SG$PartTime <- car::recode(Data_SG$Employ, "c(2,4)=1; c(1,3,5,6,7,8,9)=0")
Data_SG$SelfEmploy <- car::recode(Data_SG$Employ, "c(3,4)=1; c(1,2,5,6,7,8,9)=0")
Data_SG$Unemploy <- car::recode(Data_SG$Employ, "c(6,7)=1; c(1,2,3,4,5,8,9)=0")
#Data_SG$Student <- car::recode(Data_SG$Employ, "9=1; 1:8=0")

Descriptive Statistics

658 of 801 respondents report having used some form of a TNC service. Of those, 576 report having used an exclusive service and 364 report having used a pooled service.

#For all respondents who report having used some type of TNC service:
Data_SG_RH <- filter(Data_SG, RH_NoUse==0) 
Data_SG_RH$PRH_Trips <- as.numeric(Data_SG_RH$PRH_Trips_10)
Data_SG_RH$SRH_Trips <- as.numeric(Data_SG_RH$SRH_Trips_2)
Data_SG_RH <- Data_SG_RH %>% mutate(
        PRH_Trips = ifelse(RH_PrivUse==0, 0, PRH_Trips),
        SRH_Trips = ifelse(RH_ShareUse==0, 0, SRH_Trips))

#Create new variables: the total number of ridehailing trips the respondent has taken and the percentage or ridehailing trips that are shared/pooled
Data_SG_RH <- Data_SG_RH %>% mutate(
        RH_Trips = PRH_Trips + SRH_Trips,
        PropShare = ifelse(RH_Trips==0, 0, (SRH_Trips/RH_Trips)))
#Number of TNC trips (count) has mean = 6.259, but variance = 54.66

Post-hoc Power Analysis

#https://www.statmethods.net/stats/power.html
#n is the sample size, 
#d is the effect size, and 
#type indicates a two-sample t-test, one-sample t-test or paired t-test. If you have unequal sample sizes, use pwr.t2n.test(n1 = , n2= , d = , sig.level =, power = )

#Cohen, 1988 suggests that d values of 0.2, 0.5, and 0.8 represent small, medium, and large effect sizes respectively
pwr.t.test(n = 801, d = 0.1, sig.level = 0.05, power = , type = "one.sample")
##

#Explore rootogram for fit
#The red curved line is the theoretical Poisson fit. "Hanging" from each point on the red line is a bar, the height of which represents the difference between expected and observed counts. A bar hanging below 0 indicates underfitting. A bar hanging above 0 indicates overfitting.
countreg::rootogram(poissonfit)

#We see significant misfit; underfitting of lower values and overfitting of higher values
#This is not surprising since we know our data violates the poisson distribution assumption of equal mean and variance
#Next we will use a Negative Binomial Regression
nbrfit <- glm.nb(RH_Trips ~ Age + Male + ColDeg + GradDeg + FullTime + Student 
            + HHInc + OwnsCar + HHPers, data=Data_SG_RH)
summary(nbrfit)

#Visually, this fit looks better

#We can empirically check if this negative binomial regression (which includes a dispersion parameter) is an improvement of fit over our poisson model (nested likelihood-ratio chi-square test)
logLik(nbrfit)     # -1719.717 (df=11)
## 'log Lik.' -1712.177 (df=11)
logLik(poissonfit) # -2798.168 (df=10)
## 'log Lik.' -2789.691 (df=10)
pchisq(2 * (logLik(nbrfit) - logLik(poissonfit)), df = 1, lower.tail = FALSE)
## 'log Lik.' 0 (df=11)
#This strongly suggests that the negative binomial model is more appropriate than the Poisson model
rsq(nbrfit, type="lr") #McFadden, Cox, and Snell
## [1] 0.09732445
#To capture significance of the predictors, we can compare models with and without each predictor (otherwise overdispersion parameter is held constant)
#Use a two dof chi-square test
nbrfit_age <- update(nbrfit, . ~ . - Age)
anova(nbrfit, nbrfit_age) #age is a statistically significant predictor of RH_Trips
## Likelihood ratio tests of Negative Binomial Models
## 
## Response: RH_Trips
##                                                                           Model
## 1       Male + ColDeg + GradDeg + FullTime + Student + HHInc + OwnsCar + HHPers
## 2 Age + Male + ColDeg + GradDeg + FullTime + Student + HHInc + OwnsCar + HHPers
##       theta Resid. df    2 x log-lik.   Test    df LR stat.      Pr(Chi)
## 1 0.9033460       593       -3469.622                                   
## 2 0.9914063       592       -3424.353 1 vs 2     1 45.26916 1.717326e-11
nbrfit_male <- update(nbrfit, . ~ . - Male)
anova(nbrfit, nbrfit_male)
## Likelihood ratio tests of Negative Binomial Models
## 
## Response: RH_Trips

Proportion of TNC trips that were pooled in the last month

Data_SG_RHShared <- filter(Data_SG_RH, RH_ShareUse==1)
#Beta regression is most commonly used to predict proportions, but beta regression is used for dependent variables in the range of (0,1), exclusive of the endpoints.
#We have respondents who use pooling for 0% or 100% of their trips, so we need to first transform the data according to Smithson and Verkuilen (2006): (y * (n - 1) + 0.5)/n, where n is the sample size (i.e., 801)

Data_SG_RHShared <- Data_SG_RHShared %>% mutate(PropShare=(PropShare*800 + 0.5)/801)

#Initial beta regression using standard logistic link function
betafit <- betareg::betareg(PropShare ~ Age + Male + ColDeg + GradDeg + FullTime + Student + HHInc + OwnsCar + HHPers, data=Data_SG_RHShared)

What modes are TNC trips replacing?

Alt_names <- c('ResponseId', 'PRH_Alt_1', 'PRH_Alt_2', 'PRH_Alt_3', 'PRH_Alt_4', 'PRH_Alt_5', 'PRH_Alt_6', 'PRH_Alt_7',
               'SRH_Alt_1', 'SRH_Alt_2', 'SRH_Alt_3', 'SRH_Alt_4', 'SRH_Alt_5', 'SRH_Alt_6', 'SRH_Alt_7')
Data_SG[, Alt_names] <- apply(Data_SG[, Alt_names], 2, function(x) as.numeric(x)) #warning: blanks are replaced by NAs
Data_SG[, c('PRH_Trips_10','SRH_Trips_2')] <- apply(Data_SG[, c('PRH_Trips_10','SRH_Trips_2')], 2, function(x) as.numeric(x))

#Multiply percentage of trips replacing a given mode (Alt1-7) by reported number of trips for each individual (frequency weighting)
Data_SG <- Data_SG %>% mutate(PRH_Trip_1 = PRH_Alt_1*PRH_Trips_10, PRH_Trip_2 = PRH_Alt_2*PRH_Trips_10, PRH_Trip_3 = PRH_Alt_3*PRH_Trips_10, 
                              PRH_Trip_4 = PRH_Alt_4*PRH_Trips_10, PRH_Trip_5 = PRH_Alt_5*PRH_Trips_10, PRH_Trip_6 = PRH_Alt_6*PRH_Trips_10, 
                              PRH_Trip_7 = PRH_Alt_7*PRH_Trips_10,
                              SRH_Trip_1 = SRH_Alt_1*SRH_Trips_2, SRH_Trip_2 = SRH_Alt_2*SRH_Trips_2, SRH_Trip_3 = SRH_Alt_3*SRH_Trips_2, 
                              SRH_Trip_4 = SRH_Alt_4*SRH_Trips_2, SRH_Trip_5 = SRH_Alt_5*SRH_Trips_2, SRH_Trip_6 = SRH_Alt_6*SRH_Trips_2, 
                              SRH_Trip_7 = SRH_Alt_7*SRH_Trips_2)

#Aggregate for private and for shared separately:
#   sum adjusted number of trips by mode across individuals
PRH_Trip_Tot <- c(sum(Data_SG$PRH_Trip_1, na.rm=TRUE), sum(Data_SG$PRH_Trip_2, na.rm=TRUE), sum(Data_SG$PRH_Trip_3, na.rm=TRUE), 
                  sum(Data_SG$PRH_Trip_4, na.rm=TRUE), sum(Data_SG$PRH_Trip_5, na.rm=TRUE), sum(Data_SG$PRH_Trip_6, na.rm=TRUE), 
                  sum(Data_SG$PRH_Trip_7, na.rm=TRUE))
SRH_Trip_Tot <- c(sum(Data_SG$SRH_Trip_1, na.rm=TRUE), sum(Data_SG$SRH_Trip_2, na.rm=TRUE), sum(Data_SG$SRH_Trip_3, na.rm=TRUE), 
                  sum(Data_SG$SRH_Trip_4, na.rm=TRUE), sum(Data_SG$SRH_Trip_5, na.rm=TRUE), sum(Data_SG$SRH_Trip_6, na.rm=TRUE), 
                  sum(Data_SG$SRH_Trip_7, na.rm=TRUE))
Trip_Tot <- PRH_Trip_Tot + SRH_Trip_Tot
#   divide these sums by the total number of trips across all modes and all individuals
#   output is the total mode substitution of ridehail trips (excluding trips that would have been taken by another ridehailing service)
PRH_Tot <- sum(PRH_Trip_Tot)
SRH_Tot <- sum(SRH_Trip_Tot)
All_Tot <- sum(Trip_Tot)
PRH_Pcnt <- (PRH_Trip_Tot/PRH_Tot)*100
SRH_Pcnt <- (SRH_Trip_Tot/SRH_Tot)*100
Tot_Pcnt <- (Trip_Tot/All_Tot)*100

modes_SG <- c("Personal car", "Exclusive TNC", "Pooled TNC", "Motorcycle", "Taxi", "Public transit", "Walking or biking", "None (induced demand)")
modes_PRH <- c("Personal car", "Pooled TNC", "Motorcycle", "Taxi", "Public transit", "Walking or biking", "None (induced demand)")
modes_SRH <- c("Personal car", "Exclusive TNC", "Motorcycle", "Taxi", "Public transit", "Walking or biking", "None (induced demand)")
ModeSub_PRH <- data.frame(modes_PRH, PRH_Pcnt)
colnames(ModeSub_PRH) <- c("Mode","Exclusive TNC Trips")
ModeSub_SRH <- data.frame(modes_SRH, SRH_Pcnt)
colnames(ModeSub_SRH) <- c("Mode","Pooled TNC Trips")
ModeSub_SG <- data.frame(modes_SG) 
colnames(ModeSub_SG) <- c("Mode")
ModeSub_SG <- merge(ModeSub_SG, ModeSub_PRH, by="Mode", all.x=TRUE)
ModeSub_SG <- merge(ModeSub_SG, ModeSub_SRH, by="Mode", all.x=TRUE)

ModeSub_SG_long <- reshape2::melt(ModeSub_SG, id.vars="Mode")

#grouped bar chart
ModeSub_SG_long$Mode <- factor(ModeSub_SG_long$Mode, levels=c("Personal car", "Motorcycle", "Taxi", "Exclusive TNC", "Pooled TNC", "Public transit", "Walking or biking", "None (induced demand)"))
fig2 <- ggplot(ModeSub_SG_long, aes(y=value, x=Mode, fill=variable, label=round(value,0))) + 
  geom_bar(position="dodge", stat="identity", width=0.6)+
  geom_text(position=position_dodge(width=.6), hjust=0.6, vjust=-0.5, size=4)+
  geom_text(data=filter(ModeSub_SG_long, variable=="Exclusive TNC Trips"), aes(x="Exclusive TNC", y=1, label="NA"), 
            position=position_dodge(width=0.6), hjust=1.2, size=4, color="#440154FF")+
  geom_text(data=filter(ModeSub_SG_long, variable=="Pooled TNC Trips"), aes(x="Pooled TNC", y=1, label="NA"), 
            position=position_dodge(width=0.6), hjust=-.2, size=4, color="#FDE725FF")+
  scale_fill_viridis(option="viridis", discrete=TRUE)+
  scale_y_continuous(limits=c(0,42), expand=c(0,0))+
  ylab("Percent")+
  theme(legend.position=c(.85,.9), legend.title = element_blank(),
        legend.text=element_text(size=12), axis.title = element_text(size=14),
        axis.line = element_line(size=0.5),
        axis.text = element_text(size=14),
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust=1),
        #axis.text.x=element_blank(), axis.text.y=element_blank(), 
        axis.ticks.x=element_blank(), axis.ticks.y=element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "lightgrey"), 
        panel.grid.minor = element_line(colour = "lightgrey"))
fig2
